f the news to cover actual, real events. And all it wouldâ€™ve taken to fix this whole thing was a single phone call to an astronomer. The story wouldâ€™ve still been fun and playful, but it also wouldâ€™ve been accurate and had real science in it. Shouldnâ€™t that be the goal of all such stories?</p><p><font size=\"-2\"><em>Tip oâ€™ the probe to <a href=\"http://sciencebasedparenting.com/2010/10/14/new-york-city-ufos-or-gran-via-balloons/\" target=\"_blank\">Colin Thornton</a> for the balloon stories, and <a href=\"http://www.palaeolithic.nl/\" target=\"_blank\">Dr. Marco Langbroek</a> for the tip about the Fox story, and Jupiter.</em></font></p><p><br clear=\"all\"></p><hr width=\"30%\" align=\"left\"><font size=\"-1\"><em></p><p>Related posts:</p><p>- <a href=\"http://blogs.discovermagazine.com/badastronomy/2010/10/03/its-a-ufo-by-jove/\" target=\"_blank\">Itâ€™s a UFO, by jove</a><br />
