om the telescope to the comet and back to Earth, they can create a map of the cometâ€™s shape and other characteristics â€” something like how dolphins and bats use echolocation to map their surroundingsâ€¦ though, as Emily Lakdawalla at The Planetary Society Blog explains, <a href=\"http://www.planetary.org/blog/article/00002462/\" target=\"_blank\">itâ€™s a bit more complicated</a>.</p><p>From the images, it looks like the nucleus â€” the solid, central part of a comet â€” is highly elongated, about 2.2 km (1.4 miles) in length, and rotates once every 18 hours. Weâ€™ve only seen a handful of comets up close, and in general the nuclei are potato-shaped, so this one fits that description. <a href=\"http://www.naic.edu/~pradar/103P/\" target=\"_blank\">The image</a> has a scale of about 75 meters per pixel.</p><p>These observations were made to help out <a href=\"http://blogs.discovermagazine.com/badastronomy/2008/02/10/epoxi-sticks-like-glue-to-extrasolar-planets/\" target=\"_blank\">the EPOXI space mission</a>, which will pass just 700 km (420 miles) from the nucleus of Hartley 2 on November 4. That means weâ€™ll be getting some really cool close-up images and data from the comet very soon! Stay Tuned.</p><p><br clear=\"all\"></p><p><a href=\"http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/7xN3uzqjlGO3A2yuqLGU7d4bLWs/0/da\"><img src=\"http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/7xN3uzqjlGO3A2yuqLGU7d4bLWs/0/di\" border=\"0\" ismap=\"true\"></img></a><br/><a href=\"http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/7xN3uzqjlGO3A2yuqLGU7d4bLWs/1/da\"><img src=\"http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/7xN3uzqjlGO3A2yuqLGU7d4bLWs/1/di\" border=\"0\" ismap=\"true\"></img></a></p><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/BadAstronomyBlog/~4/1ggApvfDxSI\" height=\"1\" width=\"1\"/>" "http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/BadAstronomyBlog/~3/1ggApvfDxSI/" (19658 63879) new 2 nil nil ((title nil "Arecibo gives comet some radar love") (link nil "http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/BadAstronomyBlog/~3/1ggApvfDxSI/") (comments nil "http://blogs.discovermagazine.com/badastronomy/2010/10/29/arecibo-gives-comet-some-radar-love/#comments") (pubDate nil "Fri, 29 Oct 2010 16:42:47 +0000") (dc:creator nil "Phil Plait") (category nil "Astronomy") (category nil "Space") (category nil "Arecibo") (category nil "Comet Hartley 2") (category nil "comets") (category nil "radar") (guid ((isPermaLink . "false")) "http://blogs.discovermagazine.com/badastronomy/?p=23296") (description nil "Using a giant radio telescope like a cop&#8217;s radar gun, astronomers have made some pretty cool images of the nucleus of the comet Hartley 2:

Hartley 2 is a comet that is currently very close to the Earth as these things go: last week it passed us at a distance of about 18 million km (11 [...]") (content:encoded nil "<p>Using a giant radio telescope like a cop&#8217;s radar gun, <a href=\"http://www.jpl.nasa.gov/news/news.cfm?release=2010-358\" target=\"_blank\">astronomers have made some pretty cool images</a> of the nucleus of the comet Hartley 2:</p><p><a href=\"http://www.jpl.nasa.gov/news/news.cfm?release=2010-358\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"http://blogs.discovermagazine.com/badastronomy/files/2010/10/arecibo_hartley2.jpg\" alt=\"arecibo_hartley2\" title=\"arecibo_hartley2\" width=\"470\" height=\"350\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-23297\" /></a><br clear=\"all\"></p><p><a href=\"http://blogs.discovermagazine.com/badastronomy/2010/10/08/three-views-to-a-comet/\" target=\"_blank\">Hartley 2</a> is a comet that is currently very close to the Earth as these things go: last week it passed us at a distance of about 18 million km (11 million miles). Astronomers took advantage of the close pass to ping the comet with radar pulses. By timing exactly how long it took the pulses to go from the telescope to the comet and back to Earth, they can create a map of the comet&#8217;s shape and other characteristics &#8212; something like how dolphins and bats use echolocation to map their surroundings&#8230; though, as Emily Lakdawalla at The Planetary Society Blog explains, <a href=\"http://www.planetary.org/blog/article/00002462/\" target=\"_blank\">it&#8217;s a bit more complicated</a>.</p><p>From the images, it looks like the nucleus &#8212; the solid, central part of a comet &#8212; is highly elongated, about 2.2 km (1.4 miles) in length, and rotates once every 18 hours. We&#8217;ve only seen a handful of comets up close, and in general the nuclei are potato-shaped, so this one fits that description. <a href=\"http://www.naic.edu/~pradar/103P/\" target=\"_blank\">The image</a> has a scale of about 75 meters per pixel.</p><p>These observations were made to help out <a href=\"http://blogs.discovermagazine.com/badastronomy/2008/02/10/epoxi-sticks-like-glue-to-extrasolar-planets/\" target=\"_blank\">the EPOXI space mission</a>, which will pass just 700 km (420 miles) from the nucleus of Hartley 2 on November 4. That means we&#8217;ll be getting some really cool close-up images and data from the comet very soon! Stay Tuned.</p><p><br clear=\"all\"></p><p><a href=\"http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/7xN3uzqjlGO3A2yuqLGU7d4bLWs/0/da\"><img src=\"http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/7xN3uzqjlGO3A2yuqLGU7d4bLWs/0/di\" border=\"0\" ismap=\"true\"></img></a><br/><a href=\"http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/7xN3uzqjlGO3A2yuqLGU7d4bLWs/1/da\"><img src=\"http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/7xN3uzqjlGO3A2yuqLGU7d4bLWs/1/di\" border=\"0\" ismap=\"true\"></img></a></p><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/BadAstronomyBlog/~4/1ggApvfDxSI\" height=\"1\" width=\"1\"/>") (wfw:commentRss nil "http://blogs.discovermagazine.com/badastronomy/2010/10/29/arecibo-gives-comet-some-radar-love/feed/") (slash:comments nil "10") (feedburner:origLink nil "http://blogs.discovermagazine.com/badastronomy/2010/10/29/arecibo-gives-comet-some-radar-love/"))) ("Shuttle launch delayed a day" "<p><img src=\"http://blogs.discovermagazine.com/badastronomy/files/2010/02/sunset_shuttle-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"sunset_shuttle\" title=\"sunset_shuttle\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-11534\" />Just a quick update: <a href=\"http://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/shuttle/main/\" target=\"_blank\">NASA has delayed the launch</a> of the Space Shuttle <em>Discovery</em> by a day due to gas leaks in one of the Orbiter Maneuvering System pods (those are the engines housed under the big lumps at the rear of the Orbiter). Currently, launch is set for Tuesday, November 2 at 16:17 Eastern time. <a href=\"http://blogs.discovermagazine.com/badastronomy/2010/10/25/nasas-last-flight-of-dis