lanets, 6% have Neptune-mass ones, and about 12% have planets from 3 â€“ 10 times the Earthâ€™s mass.</p><p>This sample isnâ€™t complete, and they cannot detect planets smaller than 3 times the Earthâ€™s mass. But using some statistics, they can estimate from the trend that as many as 25% of sun-like stars have earth-mass planets orbiting them!<br /><br clear=\"all\"></p><hr width=\"10%\" align=\"left\"></p><p><strong><font size=\"+1\">L</font>ike mass?</strong></p><p>Now, thereâ€™s a <em>very</em> important caveat here: these are planets that have the same mass as Earth, <em>but that doesnâ€™t mean they are very earth-like.</em> The planets the team could find were very close to their parent stars, so theyâ€™d be very hot, and uninhabitable. But the good news is that if that trend in mass they saw is correct, the Milky Way is littered with planets the mass of the Earth! If some of them are in the habitable zone of their starâ€¦ well.</p><p><img src=\"http://blogs.discovermagazine.com/badastronomy/files/2010/10/spitzermilkyway_sunscalebar.jpg\" alt=\"spitzermilkyway_sunscalebar\" title=\"spitzermilkyway_sunscalebar\" width=\"300\" height=\"338\" class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-23227\" />So a funny thing: I was thinking about this very problem a couple of days ago, but from a different angle. How many <em>habitable</em> planets are there in the Milky Way? Not just earth-mass, but also orbiting their star in the so-called Goldilocks Zone, where temperatures are right for liquid water?</p><p>Thereâ€™s a way to estimate it. And it involves <a href=\"http://blogs.discovermagazine.com/badastronomy/2010/09/29/possible-earthlike-planet-found-in-the-goldilocks-zone-of-a-nearby-star/\" target=\"_blank\">the planet recently announced</a>, Gliese 581g. This planet is about 3 times the Earthâ€™s mass, and it orbits its star in the right place. We donâ€™t know what itâ€™s made of, if it has an atmosphere, or really very much about it at all! But given its mass and temperature, itâ€™s <em>potentially</em> habitable.</p><p>The distance to the Gliese 581 system is what gets me excited: itâ€™s 20 light years away. Thatâ€™s <em>close</em>, compared to the vast size of our galaxy. So letâ€™s assume Gliese 581g is the closest potentially habitable planet to us. Given that assumption, we can estimate the number of potentially habitable planets in the entire Milky Way! And the mathâ€™s not even that hard.<br /><span id=\"more-22840\"></span><br /><br clear=\"all\"></p><hr width=\"10%\" align=\"left\"></p><p><strong><font size=\"+1\">T</font>he not-so-hard math</strong></p><p>Extrapolating from our one example, letâ€™s say that habitable planets are roughly 20 light years apart in the galaxy (as weâ€™ll see, that number can be a lot bigger or smaller, and the end result is still cool). That means thereâ€™s one star per cube 20 light years on a side:</p><p><img src=\"http://blogs.discovermagazine.com/badastronomy/files/2010/10/sun_twocubes.jpg\" alt=\"sun_twocubes\" title=\"sun_twocubes\" width=\"433\" height=\"288\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-23234\" /></p><p>In the drawing, each box is centered on a star, and the two stars are 20 light years apart. That means the cubes are 20 light years on a side, right? If we assume stars with livable planets are distributed throughout the galaxy like this, then there is one star per 20 x 20 x 20 = <strong>8000 cubic light years</strong>. Thatâ€™s the density of habitable planets in the galaxy.</p><p>So how many cubic light years are there in the galaxy?</p><p>A <em>lot</em>. Letâ€™s say the Milky Way is a stubby cylinder 100,000 light years across, and 2500 light years thick. The equation of volume of a cylinder is</p><p><strong>volume = &pi; x radius of disk<sup>2</sup> x height of disk <br /></strong></p><p>so</p><p><strong>volume = &pi; x 50,000<sup>2</sup> x 2500 = 2 x 10<sup>13</sup> cubic light years<br /></strong></p><p>Holy wow! Thatâ€™s 20 <em>trillion</em> cubic light years! </p><p>Now we just divide the volume of the galaxy by the density of stars with planets to get</p><p><strong>2 x 10<sup>13</sup> / 8000 = 2,500,000,000 planets</strong></p><p>Oh my. Yeah, let that sink in for a second. Thatâ€™s <strong>2.5 <em>billion</em></strong> planets that are potentially habitable!<br /><br clear=\"all\"></p><hr width=\"10%\" align=\"left\"></p><p><strong><font size=\"+1\">W</font>hat does this mean?</strong></p><p>Well, thatâ€™s a whole lot of planets! <em>Thatâ€™s</em> what it means.</p><p>Whatâ€™s cool, too, is that this number isnâ€™t all that far off from what you can estimate using the report from yesterday. Something like 25% of the stars in the galaxy are like the Sun (thatâ€™s a rough estimate, but close enough). Thatâ€™s 50 billion stars. If 25% of those have earth-mass planets, thatâ€™s about 13 billion total, about five times the number I got. Iâ€™d call that pretty close! We made a lot of guesses here, so even a factor of ten isnâ€™t so bad. And weâ€™re not really comparing apples to apples, either, since they were looking for earth-<em>mass</em> planets, and I was looking for earth-<em>like</em> planets. </p><p>So think about it: 2.5 billion habitable planets is roughly enough for every man, woman, and child on Earth to each have a planet. You can see why Iâ€™m not too concerned with the exact math. Even if my numbers are way off, there could be as few as hundreds of millions of planets, or as many as maybe hundreds of <em>billions</em> in our galaxy alone that we could live on! </p><p>Again, the point being that mathematically speaking, there may be a <em>lot</em> of habitable planets out there. And who knows; some may be marginally habitable and we can terraform them. And then there are moons of worlds, tooâ€¦ I donâ€™t think Iâ€™m speaking too far out of school if I were to speculate that for every perfect <em>Terra Nova</em> out there, there might be three or four more planets we could live on with some work.</p><p>Of course, Iâ€™m ignoring how weâ€™d get there! But thatâ€™s an engineering problem, and given enough time â€” oh, say, a century or two â€” I imagine we can overcome a lot of those issues. </p><p>If, and when, we do, there will be a lot of real estate out there to poke around in. </p><p><em>Per ardua, ad astra!</em></p><p><br clear=\"all\"></p><p><a href=\"http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/owH5LNDtKQuhTRpxCo-BO8IOZaY/0/da\"><img src=\"http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/owH5LNDtKQuhTRpxCo-BO8IOZaY/0/di\" border=\"0\" ismap=\"true\"></img></a><br/><a href=\"http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/owH5LNDtKQuhTRpxCo-BO8IOZaY/1/da\"><img src=\"http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/owH5LNDtKQuhTRpxCo-BO8IOZaY/1/di\" border=\"0\" ismap=\"true\"></img></a></p><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/BadAstronomyBlog/~4/ejh3djXvZgk\" height=\"1\" width=\"1\"/>" "http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/BadAstronomyBlog/~3/ejh3djXvZgk/" (19658 50544) new 4 nil nil ((title nil "How many habitable planets are there in the galaxy?") (link nil "http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/BadAstronomyBlog/~3/ejh3djXvZgk/") (comments nil "http://blogs.discovermagazine.com/badastronomy/2010/10/29/how-many-habitable-planets-are-there-in-the-galaxy/#comments") (pubDate nil "Fri, 29 Oct 2010 13:00:32 +0000") (dc:creator nil "Phil Plait") (category nil "Astronomy") (category nil "Cool stuff") (category nil "Piece of mind") (category nil "exoplanets") (category nil "Gliese 581g") (guid ((isPermaLink . "false")) "http://blogs.discovermagazine.com/badastronomy/?p=22840") (description nil "By now you may have heard the report that as many as 1/4 of all the sun-like stars in the Milky Way may have Earth-like worlds. Briefly, astronomers studied 166 stars within 80 light years of Earth, and did a survey of the planets they found orbiting them. What they found is that about 1.5% [...]") (content:encoded nil "<p><img src=\"http://blogs.discovermagazine.com/badastronomy/files/2010/09/gliese581c-300x230.jpg\" alt=\"gliese581c\" title=\"gli